The paper uses information theory to provide measures of complexity, emergence, self-organization, and homeostasis, which are concepts commonly studied in the field of complex systems. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which often deals with complex systems and their properties. Additionally, the paper uses computational experiments, which could also place it in the sub-category of cs.IT (Information Theory). The use of networks and automata in the experiments could also suggest the sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper's focus on measuring and quantifying concepts could place it in the sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning).
